      <section eId="sec_4141">
        <num>4141</num>
        <heading>Death certificate; form and content</heading>
        <subsection eId="sec_4141__subsec_a">
          <num>(a)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The medical certificate shall be made, dated, and signed by the\nphysician or nurse practitioner, if any, last in attendance on the\ndeceased.\n</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="sec_4141__subsec_b">
          <num>(b)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Indefinite terms, denoting only symptoms of disease or conditions\nresulting from disease, shall not be held sufficient.\n</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="sec_4141__subsec_c">
          <num>(c)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Any certificate stating the cause of death in terms which the\ncommissioner declares indefinite shall be returned to the physician,\nnurse practitioner, or person making the medical certificate for\ncorrection and more definite statement.\n</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="sec_4141__subsec_d">
          <num>(d)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Where a death is caused by an opioid overdose, such information\nshall be indicated on the certificate, including, if known to the person\ncompleting the death certificate, the specific opioid that caused the\ndeath of the decedent, along with any other related information as the\ncommissioner may require.\n</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
      </section>
